{"title_page": "Snow Patrol", "text_new": "{{short description|Northern Irish-Scottish rock band}}\n{{Redirect|Snow patrol|the rescue service for skiers and participants in other snow sports|Ski patrol|and|Mountain rescue}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Snow Patrol\n| image            = Snow Patrol Band.jpg\n| caption          = Snow Patrol, from left\u2013right: [[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]], [[Gary Lightbody]], [[Jonny Quinn]], [[Nathan Connolly]], [[Tom Simpson (musician)|Tom Simpson]]\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = {{Nowrap|[[Dundee, Scotland|Dundee]], [[Scotland]], United Kingdom}}\n| alias            = Polarbear\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[power pop]]|[[post-Britpop]]|[[indie rock]]}}\n| years_active     = 1994\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Fiction Records|Fiction]]|[[A&M Records|A&M]]|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|[[Geffen Records|Geffen]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[Island Records|Island]]|[[Jeepster Records|Jeepster]]|[[Electric Honey (label)|Electric Honey]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Shrug (band)|Shrug]]|[[Iain Archer]]|[[Belle & Sebastian]]|[[The Reindeer Section]]|[[Terra Diablo]]|[[The Cake Sale]]|[[Little Doses]]|[[Listen... Tanks!]]|[[Tired Pony]]}}\n| website          = {{url|snowpatrol.com}}\n| current_members  = * [[Gary Lightbody]]\n* [[Jonny Quinn]]\n* [[Nathan Connolly]]\n* [[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]]\n* [[Johnny McDaid]]\n| past_members     =\n* [[Mark McClelland]]\n* Michael Morrison\n* [[Tom Simpson (musician)|Tom Simpson]]\n}}\n'''Snow Patrol''' are<!-- Please note that British English uses the plural \"are\" instead of the American singular \"is\" --> a Northern Irish-Scottish [[Rock music|rock]] band, formed in [[Dundee, Scotland]] in 1994,<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p337688/biography|pure_url=yes}} |title=Snow Patrol \u2013 Biography |accessdate=17 July 2008 |author=Borges, Mario Mesquita |website=[[AllMusic]] }}</ref> consisting of [[Gary Lightbody]] (vocals, guitar), [[Nathan Connolly]] (guitar, backing vocals), [[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]] (bass guitar, backing vocals), [[Jonny Quinn]] (drums), and [[Johnny McDaid]] (piano, guitar, backing vocals).<ref name=\"McDaid\">{{cite web |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1067309/snow-patrol-track-by-track-video-fallen-empires|title=Patrol Track-By-Track Video: 'Fallen Empires' |first=Lisa |last=Binkert |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref> Initially an [[indie rock]] band, the band rose to prominence in the early-mid 2000s as part of the [[post-Britpop]] movement.\n\nThe band were founded at the [[University of Dundee]] in 1994 by Lightbody, [[Mark McClelland]], and Michael Morrison as [[Shrug (band)|Shrug]]. After briefly using the name Polarbear, releasing the [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Starfighter Pilot]]'' (1997) and losing Morrison as a member, the band became Snow Patrol in 1997 and added Quinn to its line-up. Their first two studio albums, ''[[Songs for Polarbears]]'' (1998) and ''[[When It's All Over We Still Have to Clear Up]]'' (2001), were commercially unsuccessful and were released by the independent record label [[Jeepster Records]]. The band then signed to the major record label [[Polydor Records]] in 2002.\n\nConnolly joined Snow Patrol in 2002, and after their major-label debut album, ''[[Final Straw]]'', the following year, with \"[[Run (Snow Patrol song)|Run]]\" the album\u2019s major hit, the band rose to national fame. The album was certified [[Music recording sales certification|5\u00d7 platinum]] in the UK and eventually sold over 3 million copies worldwide. Their next studio album, ''[[Eyes Open]]'' (2006), and its hit single, \"[[Chasing Cars]]\"\u2014the most widely played song of the 21st century on UK radio\u2014propelled the band to greater international fame. The album topped the [[UK Albums Chart]] and was the best-selling British album of the year, selling over 6 million copies worldwide. In 2008, the band released their fifth studio album, ''[[A Hundred Million Suns]]''; then, in 2009, they released their first compilation album, ''[[Up to Now]]''; and, in 2011, released their sixth studio album, ''[[Fallen Empires (album)|Fallen Empires]]''. The band released their seventh album, ''[[Wildness (album)|Wildness]]'', on 25 May 2018.\n\nDuring the course of their career, Snow Patrol have won seven [[Meteor Music Awards#Winners|Meteor Ireland Music Awards]] and have been nominated for six [[Brit Awards]] and one [[Grammy Award]]. Since the release of ''Final Straw'', the band have sold over 16 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a176894/snow-patrol-to-release-greatest-hits.html|title=Snow Patrol to release greatest hits|last=Balls|first=David|date=11 September 2009|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=11 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years (1994\u20131997)===\n{{Main|Snow Patrol discography}}\n\n[[File:Shrug - December 1994.jpg|thumb|Snow Patrol originated from a band called [[Shrug (band)|Shrug]], which formed in 1994 and consisted of [[Gary Lightbody]], Michael Morrison and [[Mark McClelland]].]]\n\nSnow Patrol were originally formed in early 1994 by [[University of Dundee]] students [[Gary Lightbody]], [[Mark McClelland]], and Michael Morrison under the name [[Shrug (band)|Shrug]].<ref name=\"brianbebo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/music/interviews/snow-patrol-video-interview-quiz-biography-pictures.html |title=Snow Patrol |publisher=[[Channel 4]] |accessdate=14 October 2008 }}</ref> The band started by performing gigs at the university and surrounding pubs such as Lucifer's Mill. Their first EP was entitled \"The Yogurt vs. Yoghurt Debate.\" In 1996, they changed their name to Polarbear to avoid issues with any American bands that were also named Shrug. Shortly afterwards, drummer Michael Morrison left the band after suffering a breakdown and returned to Northern Ireland. In mid-1997, Polarbear released a three-track [[Extended play|EP]], ''[[Starfighter Pilot]]'', on the [[Electric Honey (label)|Electric Honey]] label.<ref name=\"pilotis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=10&aid=410 |title=Snow Patrol \u2013 Starfighter Pilot EP |accessdate=17 July 2008 |publisher=[[Interscope Records]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207020739/http://www.interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=10&aid=410 |archivedate=7 February 2009 }}</ref> The band again renamed, this time to Snow Patrol in 1997,<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> because of a naming conflict with [[Polar Bear (American band)|another band]] of the same name fronted by [[Jane's Addiction]]'s ex-bassist [[Eric Avery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/band|title=Biography|website=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> At this point, [[Jonny Quinn]], from Northern Ireland, joined as permanent drummer.\n\n===''Songs for Polarbears'' and ''When It's All Over We Still Have to Clear Up'' (1997\u20132001)===\nSnow Patrol joined independent label [[Jeepster Records|Jeepster]] in 1997, home of [[Belle & Sebastian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/music-magazine/music-magazine-features/label-profile/label-profile-jeepster-772565.html |title=Label profile: Jeepster |last=Birke |first=Sarah |date=23 January 2008 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=10 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kww0nasi |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> Jeepster had the same idea for Snow Patrol as the approach they had with Belle & Sebastian, who had become popular by word-of-mouth, without heavy promotion. The band were happy to be associated with an indie label, because it provided them greater independence than a major label. At that time, they were quoted as saying they expected Jeepster wouldn't expect them to have a strict work ethic or focus too much on promotional efforts.<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/07/24/1090464906092.html |title=That's Snow business |date=25 July 2004 |newspaper=[[The Age]]|accessdate=29 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kskyWtQq |archivedate=29 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nSnow Patrol's debut album was ''[[Songs for Polarbears]]'', released in 1998 after the band had started living in [[Glasgow]].<ref name=\"BASED\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/3578509.stm |title=Ice cool band warms hearts |date=29 March 2004 |website=BBC |accessdate=1 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kx9XO83x |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> Lightbody was then working at the Nice n Sleazy's Bar in [[Sauchiehall Street]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotland.org/about/entertainment-and-sport/features/culture/scottish-music.html |title=Scottish Music in the US |date=March 2007 |website=Scotland.org |accessdate=1 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ky5GX6DI |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> The album was a critical success, but did not make any impact commercially.<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\"/> The same year, the band came close to getting featured in a worldwide advertisement for [[Philips]]. [[Gomez (band)|Gomez]] was ultimately signed.<ref name=\"GOMEZ\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/415858.html|title=Licensed to chill|last=Bailie|first=Stuart|date=3 February 1999|magazine=Hot Press|accessdate=4 January 2010}} ''Appears as:'' \"This may be a reference to the fact that they almost got the worldwide gig for the Phillips TV ad, which would have required them to sing a version of The Beatles It's Getting Better. But some wires got crossed, and Gomez took the job instead.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/gomez/articles/story/5926916/gomez_get_fabulous_for_philips_advertisement |title=Gomez get fabulous for Philips advertisement |last=Boehlert |first=Eric |date=12 November 1998 |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=4 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mWyBQDXG |archivedate=4 January 2010 }}</ref> In 1999, the band won the \"Phil Lynott Award for Best New Band\" by Irish music magazine ''[[Hot Press]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/1638726.html|title=Belle Fest|last=Sweeney|first=Eamon|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|accessdate=1 October 2009}} Note: Archived page can be found here [https://www.webcitation.org/5lFXHuaUT?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20001002071324/www.hot-press.com/inawards.htm</ref> In 2001, still living in Glasgow, the band followed up with ''[[When It's All Over We Still Have to Clear Up]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kexp.org/reviews/albumreview.aspx?reviewid=691 |title=Snow Patrol: When It's All Over We Still Have to Clear Up |last=Yates |first=Don |date=15 May 2001 |publisher=[[KEXP-FM|KEXP]] |accessdate=1 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ky0ZzB95 |archivedate=1 November 2009 }}</ref> Like its predecessor, the album was praised by critics, but did not sell.<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\"/>\n\nThe band began to work harder and tour more. They slept on fans' floors after concerts and pretended to be members of [[Belle & Sebastian]] to get into nightclubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6895899.ece |title=Snow Patrol: 'We're not ready for greatest hits' |last=Heawood |first=Sophie |date=30 October 2009 |newspaper=The Times |accessdate=31 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kvhEAV7s |archivedate=31 October 2009 }}</ref> They owed rent to their landlords and used to receive regular visits and letters from them when on tour.<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\"/> After the failure of the second album, the band began to realise that the label's lax attitude towards management and record promotion, qualities that had initially attracted the band to Jeepster, was likely holding them back. The band's manager at the time was Danny McIntosh. Lightbody has described him as \"the angriest man in pop: great, great man\". He has said that he loved the band \"with every atom in his body\", and was never angry towards them. He has credited him with keeping the band together in those years. McIntosh had a gold coloured splitter bus in which the band used to travel to play concerts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2009/11/23/snow-patrol-get-revolutionary-with-back-catalogue/ |title=Snow Patrol get revolutionary with back catalogue |last=Dowling |first=Stephen |date=23 November 2009 |publisher=[[Spinner.com]] |accessdate=24 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130630090442/http://www.spinner.com/2009/11/23/snow-patrol-get-revolutionary-with-back-catalogue/ |archivedate=30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJeepster dropped Snow Patrol in 2001,<ref name=\"WOWJONNY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsonwales.co.uk/news/i/12550 |title=Snow Patrol Interview |last=Took |first=Michael |publisher=What's on Wales |accessdate=24 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCajNdyB |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> a decision that was criticised by ''[[Hot Press]]'' magazine as brainless.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/1610824.html|title=The Northern Alliance|last=Carberry|first=Colin|magazine=Hot Press|accessdate=1 October 2009}} Note: Archived page, can be found here [https://archive.is/20120709225319/http://google.com/search?q=cache:QJpQysy-Q5UJ:www.hotpress.com/archive/1610824.html+http://www.hotpress.com/archive/1610824.html&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=in&client=firefox-a].</ref> By July 2001, many major labels had started showing interest in Snow Patrol,<ref name=\"MANAGERCOMMENTS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/1610710.html |title=The popular music digest |last=Clark |first=Stuart |magazine=Hot Press|accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712015744/http://www.hotpress.com/archive/1610710.html |archivedate=12 July 2009 }} Note: Archived page, can be found here .</ref> but the band were cash-strapped and had no record deal.<ref name=\"SIGNINGFICTION\">{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,,24780365-5003421,00.html |title=Snow Patrol comes in from the cold |last=Mengel |first=Noel |date=11 December 2008 |work=News.com.au |publisher=Queensland Newspapers |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCdLC4bO |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> Lightbody sold a major part of his record collection to raise money to keep the band going. Lightbody calls the time \"miserable\", but was confident of getting signed to another label quickly. However, the music scene in the United Kingdom had turned its attention to American bands and British bands were not getting signed. The band spent this time constantly writing songs. Lightbody, bored at this point, assembled [[The Reindeer Section]], a Scottish [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]], and found a record label to release the group's recordings.<ref name=\"Y!MUSIC\">{{cite web|url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/interview/14128556 |title=Let It Snow, Let It Snow, Let It Snow |last=DiMartino |first=Dave |date=11 April 2007 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCtYdP5C |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> Quinn said that though the time was hard for everyone involved except for Nathan, the question of splitting up never arose. It was during this time the band wrote \"[[Run (Snow Patrol song)|Run]]\" (which had been around since 2000)<ref name=\"SIGNINGFICTION\"/> in a room on an acoustic guitar, which later became the band's breakthrough single. The band's \"low point\" came when they played a concert to 18 people at a popular strip club in [[High Wycombe]].<ref name=\"WOWJONNY\"/><ref name=\"WYCOMBE\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article390316.ece |title=Band on a run |last=Rose |first=Hilary |date=12 November 2004 |newspaper=The Times |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCvETez5 |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article1018127.ece |title=The flaky success of Snow Patrol |last=Jelbert |first=Steve |date=13 February 2004 |newspaper=The Times |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCwW5mc1 |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> The show took place in a shoddy VIP area, and the management had to unscrew poles used by pole dancers to make space for the band to play, something that Gary would later joke about whilst performing at a sold out Wembley Arena. Quinn calls the show \"horrendous\". Desperate for attention, the band raised \u00a3200 to nominate themselves for a Mercury Prize, but failed to get shortlisted.<ref name=\"WYCOMBE\"/>\n\n=== ''Final Straw'' (2002\u20132005)===\nIn 2002, the band started to be managed and published by [[Jazz Summers]] of [[Big Life]].<ref name=\"SUMMERS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/snow-patrol-split-from-manager_1030971 |title=Snow Patrol split from manager |date=15 May 2007 |magazine=[[Contactmusic.com]] |accessdate=6 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5l1Nzr3ij |archivedate=4 November 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/2923995.html|title=Snow Patrol part with manager|date=11 May 2007|magazine=Hot Press|accessdate=6 October 2009}} Note: Archived page, can be found here [https://google.com/search?q=cache:D7aPjNBXGZsJ:dvl.hotpress.com/Snow%2520Patrol/news/Snow%2520Patrol%2520part%2520with%2520manager/2923995.html+http://www.hotpress.com/news/2923995.html&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=in&client=firefox-a]{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nathan Connolly - Snow Patrol.jpg|thumb|right|Nathan Connolly was asked to join the band in 2002.]]\nGuitarist [[Nathan Connolly]], previously a member of the band [[File Under Easy Listening]]<ref name=\"Y!MUSIC\"/> had been working in an [[HMV Group|HMV]] store room in Belfast at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article390316.ece?token=null |title=Band on a Run |last=Rose |first=Hilary |date=12 November 2004 |newspaper=The Times |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCvkcbHO |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> Connolly and the band had a mutual friend, who introduced them to him. Connolly moved to Glasgow to join the band in the spring of 2002.<ref name=\"NATHANJOINING\">{{cite web|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/entertainment/fun/35152264.html?showAll=y |title=Snow Patrol enjoys avalanche of success |last=Wirt |first=John |date=28 November 2008 |publisher=2theadvocate |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCy0Fc3O |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/theampersand/archive/2008/10/27/on-tour-with-snow-patrol-dublin-homecoming.aspx |title=On tour with Snow Patrol: Dublin homecoming |last=Frenette |first=Brad |date=27 October 2008 |newspaper=[[National Post]] |accessdate=24 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5l1NhFiB2 |archivedate=4 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Lightbody and McClelland's years at the University of Dundee, they had been noticed by Richard Smernicki, a senior student. Through Richard, brother [[Paul Smernicki|Paul]] too had come to know the band. Richard graduated in 1996, two years before Lightbody and McClelland, to become [[Polydor Records|Polydor's]] Scottish [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] representative. Paul became Polydor's Press and Artist Development Manager<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/pressoffice/actualreuniteddocument.pdf |title=Route 66 to Rock |last=Smernicki |first=Paul |publisher=[[University of Dundee]] |page=8 |accessdate=20 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kdx06ptC |archivedate=19 October 2009 }}</ref> and [[Fiction Records|Fiction's]] label manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/pressreleases/2006/week241106.htm |title=In tune with the iPod generation |last=Wilson |first=Alan |date=22 November 2006 |publisher=University of Dundee. [[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]] |accessdate=20 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kf3TWKnk |archivedate=20 October 2009 }}</ref> Later, Jim Chancellor, an A&R executive for Fiction, and fellow talent scout Alex Close<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.addressuniversal.com/ |title=Interview&nbsp;\u2013 Jim Chancellor, A&R Fiction/Universal UK |date=26 October 2005 |publisher=Universal Music Group |accessdate=20 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kf1JxS0V |archivedate=20 October 2009 }}</ref> approached the band in Glasgow to listen to their demos, and judged them on \"the quality of the songs\", according to Lightbody.<ref name=\"SIGNINGFICTION\"/><ref name=\"SPONFUTURE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.teletext.co.uk/planetsound/interviews-features/9a3ff3551302d614811fd5c38f428dc1/Snow+Patrol+on+their+future.aspx |title=Snow Patrol on their future |last=Earls |first=John |publisher=[[Planet Sound]]. [[Teletext Ltd.|Teletext]] |accessdate=23 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lVIk6zke |archivedate=23 November 2009 }}</ref> Chancellor introduced them to producer [[Jacknife Lee]], who despite having been a guitarist in 1990s punk rock band [[Compulsion (band)|Compulsion]] had no rock production experience at that point, being known at the time for his work with [[Basement Jaxx]] and [[Eminem]].<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\"/><ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_JimChanc.html |title=Interview With Jim Chancellor |publisher=[[HitQuarters]] |date=26 October 2005 |accessdate=30 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905141043/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_JimChanc.html |archive-date=5 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muzika.hr/clanak/22192/interview/nathan-connolly-snow-patrol-s-vremenom-postajemo-veci-bend-i-nemamo-straha-izaci-na-jednu-od-najvecih-pozornica-ikada.aspx|title=Interview \u2013 Nathan Connolly (Snow Patrol)|last=Jurilj|first=Igor|date=4 August 2009|publisher=Muzika|language=Croatian|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kCKZVhAH|archivedate=1 October 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=1 October 2009}} Note: Translation can be found here [http://garylightbody.wordpress.com/2009/09/08/muzika-hr-interview/]{{dead link|date=May 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}.</ref>\n\n''[[Final Straw]]'' was released on 4 August 2003, under Black Lion, a subsidiary of Polydor Records.<ref name=\"BASED\"/> Its music was along the same lines as the band's first two albums, and no attempt was made to change the sound to something more radio-friendly.<ref name=\"STRUGGLE\"/><ref name=\"BASED\"/> The release of ''Final Straw'' in the US in 2004 saw the album sell more than 250,000 copies and become the 26th-most popular album in the UK of that year. The album was eventually certified five times platinum in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bpi.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=Bpi.co.uk |date= |accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> In mid-2005, during their tour to support ''Final Straw'', the band toured with [[U2]] as an opening act on the [[Vertigo Tour]] in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u2exit.com/2005/03/vertigo_tour_dates.php|title=Vertigo Tour Dates|publisher=u2exit.com | date=27 March 2005 |accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> That summer also saw Snow Patrol playing a short set in London at the worldwide benefit concert [[Live 8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelive8concert.com/snow_patrol.htm|title=Snow Patrol at Live 8|publisher=thelive8concert.com (unofficial site)|accessdate=12 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628022739/http://www.thelive8concert.com/snow_patrol.htm|archivedate=28 June 2010}}</ref> After finishing their opening act duties and extensive 2-year tour of ''Final Straw'' in late July, the band took a few weeks off and began writing and recording songs for a new album. Snow Patrol's new version of [[John Lennon]]'s \"[[Isolation (John Lennon song)|Isolation]]\" was released on 10 December 2005 as part of the Amnesty International campaign, [[Make Some Noise (campaign)|Make Some Noise]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.make-some-noise.org/noise.amnesty.org/site/c.adKIIVNsEkG/b.1209081/k.9BC6/Snow_Patrol.htm|title=Snow Patrol \u2013 Make Some Noise|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=12 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091029153602/http://www.make-some-noise.org/noise.amnesty.org/site/c.adKIIVNsEkG/b.1209081/k.9BC6/Snow_Patrol.htm|archivedate=29 October 2009}}</ref> The song was later issued on the 2007 John Lennon tribute album, ''[[Instant Karma: The Amnesty International Campaign to Save Darfur]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/the_leak/various_artists/instant_karma/|title=Instant Karma: The Amnesty International Campaign to Save Darfur | publisher=MTV | year=2007 | accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Eyes Open'' and worldwide success (2005\u20132007) ===\n[[File:Paul Wilson at The ABC on 1 May 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]] ''(pictured)'' replaced bassist Mark McClelland in March 2005.]]\nOn 16 March 2005, McClelland left the band, with Lightbody stating \"a whole new set of new and unexpected pressures... have unfortunately taken their toll on working relationships within the band, and it was felt the band could not move forward with Mark as a member.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=911|title=Message from Gary|publisher=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> At the end of March 2005, former [[Terra Diablo]] member [[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]] was announced as the official replacement for McClelland and Snow Patrol also declared longtime touring keyboardist [[Tom Simpson (musician)|Tom Simpson]] an official member of the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=909 |title=New Patrol member |publisher=Snowpatrol.com |accessdate=10 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224223848/http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=909 |archivedate=24 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe band completed the recording of ''[[Eyes Open]]'' in December 2005, with Jacknife Lee returning for production, and this album was released on 28 April 2006 in Ireland, and the UK on 1 May 2006, with the first UK single \"[[You're All I Have]]\" released on 24 April 2006. The album was released in North America on 9 May. While \"Hands Open\" was the first American single, \"[[Chasing Cars]]\" pushed its way onto the download and pop charts after it was heard during an emotional scene of the second-season finale of the television show ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' on 15 May 2006. On 23 July 2006, \"Chasing Cars\" had the distinction of being the last song performed live on the [[BBC|BBC's]] ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.<ref name=\"TOTP\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-49008689|title=And the most-played song on UK radio is... Chasing Cars by Snow Patrol |work=[[BBC News]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> The song peaked at number 6 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], and number 5 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8434418.stm|title=Snow Patrol's Chasing Cars is most played of decade|date=30 December 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=30 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Billboard|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Reviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hBIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA56|date=27 January 2007|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=56}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Snow Patrol at Roseland Ballroom in 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Snow Patrol on stage in New York\u2019s [[Roseland Ballroom]] in 2006]]\nOn 26 November 2006, ''Eyes Open'' had become the [[List of best-selling albums by year in the United Kingdom|best-selling album of 2006 in the UK]], selling 1.5&nbsp;million copies and 6&nbsp;million worldwide. It was also the [[List of best-selling albums of the 2000s (decade) in the United Kingdom|15th best-selling album of the 2000s]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/12_december/14/radio1.shtml |title=Radio 1 to reveal best-selling singles and albums of the Noughties |work=Press Office |publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=24 November 2011}}</ref> and is one of the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling albums in UK chart history]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-biggest-studio-albums-of-all-time__24431/|title=The UK's Top 40 biggest studio albums of time|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=13 October 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> The album reached platinum certification in the US as well, selling over 1,000,000 copies, and it maintained a spot in the upper quarter of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] list for over fifteen weeks, on the heels of the popularity of \"Chasing Cars\". The band also holds the distinction of having one of iTunes' top downloaded albums and songs of 2006. Ahead of the band's February tour, ''Eyes Open'' topped the Australian charts some eight months after its release on 22 January 2006. In Ireland, ''Eyes Open'' became one of the best selling albums of all time, staying at the top of the charts from the end of 2006 to early\u2013mid-2007, and remaining in the charts to the present.\n\nAt the [[49th Grammy Awards|2007 Grammy Awards]], \"Chasing Cars\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]], and at the [[2007 BRIT Awards|2007]] [[Brit Awards]], the song was nominated for [[2007 Brit Award|Best British Single]].<ref name=\"Brits\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/snow-patrol |title=Snow Patrol |publisher=Brits.co.uk |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=10 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312225926/http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/snow-patrol |archivedate=12 March 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2007/grammys.htm |title=49th Annual Grammy Awards \u2013 2007 |publisher=Rock on the Net |date= |accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> 1 September 2007 saw Snow Patrol headlining a \"home coming\" mini-festival in Lightbody and Jonny Quinn's home town of [[Bangor, County Down|Bangor]], County Down. Around 30,000 people came to see the band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/snow-patrol-vow-to-return-after-hit-gig-13472158.html|title=Snow Patrol vow to return to Ward Park|accessdate=28 July 2008|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=8701|title=Snow Patrol response to Ward Park gig|accessdate=28 July 2008|publisher=Snow Patrol Official Website}}</ref>\n\n===''A Hundred Million Suns'' (2008\u20132009)===\nLightbody stated that recording for the follow-up to ''Eyes Open'' was to begin in Autumn 2006, with Jacknife Lee returning a third time for production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=16211 |title=Snow Patrol : News : Snow Patrol Announce New Album \"A Hundred Million Suns\" |publisher=Snowpatrol.com |accessdate=16 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902234450/http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=16211 |archivedate=2 September 2008 }}</ref> Since then the band stated that they wished to take a year off after the back-to-back tours of ''Final Straw'' and ''Eyes Open'' and intended to emerge at the end of 2008 with their next album.\n\n[[File:Snow Patrol at Sheffield Arena 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Snow Patrol performing at the [[Sheffield Arena]] in March 2009]]\nA post, dated 23 May 2008 on the band's official website stated that recording for the next album had been under way for a week; they began on 19 May 2008. The new album, entitled ''[[A Hundred Million Suns]]'', was released on 24 October 2008 in Ireland and 27 October in the UK and US. The first single entitled \"[[Take Back the City]]\" was released in Ireland on 10 October 2008. Filming for the music video to \"Take Back the City\" took place on 11 August 2008 in Central London. The music video was directed by [[Alex and Martin|Alex Courtes]].\n\nThe band kicked off their [[Taking Back the Cities Tour]] on 26 October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20540|title=Snow Patrol kick-off & Ireland tour!|publisher=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> Singer Miriam Kaufmann tours with the band and sings backing vocals, most notably on \"[[Set the Fire to the Third Bar]]\", which originally featured [[Martha Wainwright]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=6750|title=Update from Gary!|publisher=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> The 'UK & Ireland Arena tour' ended on 23 March. The final show was played at the [[Odyssey (Belfast)|Odyssey]] in Belfast to a 9,000 strong crowd including family and friends of the band, and the Northern Irish football squad. It also reported that the band played to an estimated 200,000 fans during the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20913|title=Snow Patrol end UK & Ireland tour in Belfast|publisher=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Snow Patrol in Frankfurt.jpg|thumb|The band\u2019s lead singer Gary Lightbody performing \u201cThe Lightning Strike\" in Frankfurt, May 2009]]\nThe band next visited South Africa to play a couple of dates at the Coca-Cola Zero Festival, supporting Oasis<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=21103|title=Update from South Africa|publisher=Snowpatrol.com|accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref> before beginning a European leg of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20583|title=New European shows announced! | publisher=Universal Music |date=25 February 2009 | accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> In June they supported [[Coldplay]] for a month on the [[Viva la Vida Tour]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20984|title=Snow Patrol to support Coldplay! |publisher=Universal Music |date=30 March 2009 | accessdate=12 May 2010 }}</ref> and joined the [[U2 360\u00b0 Tour]] in July/August.\n\nThe band also released a compilation album featuring tracks from the band's 15-year history,<ref name=\"YECOMP-SING\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/peopleNews/idUSN1933256420080920|title=Pussycat Dolls' solo work on hold for \"Domination\"|work=Reuters|accessdate=25 August 2009 | date=20 September 2008}}</ref> ''[[Up to Now]]'', on 9 November 2009. It includes thirty tracks spanning two CDs, of which three are original new songs. \"[[Just Say Yes (song)|Just Say Yes]]\", a song written by Lightbody and earlier recorded by [[Pussycat Dolls|Pussycat Doll]] [[Nicole Scherzinger]] and [[The X Factor (UK)|X Factor]] star [[Diana Vickers]], was released as the lead single<ref name=\"YECOMP-SING\"/> on 2 November. The album additionally contains past singles, covers and rarities, including songs from the band's side-project [[The Reindeer Section]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=22785|title=Snow Patrol announce new album 'Up to Now'!|publisher=Snow Patrol|accessdate=11 September 2009}}</ref> The band expressed wishes to make a tour documentary in the future, on the lines of U2's ''[[Rattle and Hum]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/celebrity/would-love-film-tour---1041321 |title=We would love to do a film of our tour&nbsp;\u2013 just like U2, says Snow Patrol's Nathan Connolly|last=Fulton|first=Rick|date=6 November 2009|newspaper=Daily Record|accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, the [[Phonographic Performance Limited|PPL]] announced \"Chasing Cars\" was the most widely played song of the decade in the UK.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news| date = 30 December 2009| author = BBC| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8434418.stm| title = Snow Patrol's Chasing Cars is most played of decade| work = BBC News| publisher = BBC| accessdate = 30 December 2009}}</ref> The same month, in a UK poll conducted by [[Channel 4]], it was voted the nation's favourite \"song of the noughties\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Gear is nation's favourite in TV poll|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/6884202/Top-Gear-is-nations-favourite-in-TV-poll.html|agency=The Telegraph|issue=26 December 2009|date=30 March 2015}}</ref> In January 2010, the band were nominated in three categories in the annual [[2010 Meteor Awards|Meteor Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2010/0107/meteornominees.html |title=Meteor Ireland Awards nominees |date=7 January 2010 |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117085832/http://www.rte.ie/arts/2010/0107/meteornominees.html |archivedate=17 January 2010 }}</ref> The band also played at the event, scheduled on 19 February 2010 at [[RDS Arena|The RDS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/music/snow-patrol-and-westlife-to-take-centre-stage-at-meteors-2003098.html |title=Snow Patrol and Westlife to take centre stage at Meteors |last=Nolan |first=Lorna |date=7 January 2010 |work=[[Evening Herald]] |accessdate=8 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mdhWWMV8 |archivedate=8 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===''Fallen Empires'' (2010\u20132012)===\nSnow Patrol said they would enter its \"next phase\" with their sixth album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/entertainment/Snow-Patrol-ready-to-enter-its-next-phase-8284274-60690012.html |title=Snow Patrol ready to enter its next phase |last=Dunham |first=Nancy |date=24 September 2009 |magazine=[[The Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kD34xuT0 |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref> The band took a new musical direction, and Connolly advised fans to keep an open mind regarding the new material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/news/Snow+Patrol-9220.html|title=Snow Patrol's new direction|publisher=Female First|accessdate=6 September 2009}}</ref> On 12 January 2011, Lightbody launched a blog to give details about the progress of the next release from the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icanhover.tumblr.com/post/2719309377/am-new-to-here-and-this-is-my-first-post-so-i|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315150408/http://icanhover.tumblr.com/post/2719309377/am-new-to-here-and-this-is-my-first-post-so-i|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 March 2011|title=2:46&nbsp;pm|last=Lightbody|first=Gary|date=12 January 2011|publisher=Tumblr|accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nSnow Patrol released the single \"[[Called Out in the Dark]]\" (remixed by [[Fatboy Slim]]) for radio airplay on Thursday 21 July 2011 on BBC Radio 1 on [[Zane Lowe]]'s radio show. According to official sources, the single itself would be released independently and as part of an EP later on and the UK release date was said to be 4 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=36060|title=Snow Patrol Return!|last=Eskimos|first=The|date=18 July 2011|publisher=snowpatrol.com|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> More details on the EP were announced on 3 August, when the group's website revealed the artwork and track list contents. Along with the new single, the release contained three new tracks entitled \"My Brothers\", \"I'm Ready\", and \"Fallen Empires\". In addition, it was revealed that the EP was intended to be a digital release limited to the UK and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=36219|title=Called Out In The Dark Ep \u2013 Tracklisting / Artwork|last=Eskimos|first=The|date=3 August 2011|publisher=snowpatrol.com|accessdate=12 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20180603 N\u00fcrnberg Rock im Park Snow Patrol 0177.jpg|thumb|[[Johnny McDaid]] joined the group in 2011 after serving as a guest musician and songwriter in the studio.]]\nShortly after the premiere of the new lead single, the quintet's official website confirmed the news that the name of the new album would be ''Fallen Empires''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=36095|title=New Snow Patrol album to be called Fallen Empires|date=22 July 2011|website=snowpatrol.com|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[Fallen Empires (album)|Fallen Empires]]'' was released on 14 November 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005NGYQTM/ref=s9_bbs_gw_d0_g15_ir01?pf_rd_m=A3P5ROKL5A1OLE&pf_rd_s=center-2&pf_rd_r=1RPAE315KJPZMK16WCXB&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_p=467128533&pf_rd_i=468294|title=Snow Patrol 'Fallen Empires' Preorder|date=16 October 2011|publisher=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref> in the UK and was launched at O2 Shepherd's Bush Empire.<ref>[http://www.marmaladelondon.co.uk/Work/Installations/20/SNOW+PATROL#20]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003001440/http://www.marmaladelondon.co.uk/Work/Installations/20/SNOW%2BPATROL|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> Singer-songwriter [[Johnny McDaid]], after being involved in the album as a guest musician and songwriter, would then join the band on the subsequent tour and eventually become a full member of Snow Patrol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.threee.com/client/johnny-mcdaid/|title=Johnny McDaid|publisher=Threee|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second single from ''Fallen Empires'' was \"This Isn't Everything You Are\", released on 13 November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/default.aspx?nid=36682|title=This Isn't Everything You are Release Date|date=28 September 2011|publisher= snowpatrol.net|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===''Greatest Hits'' (2013\u20132018)===\nThe band released a compilation entitled ''[[Greatest Hits (Snow Patrol album)|Greatest Hits]]'' on 14 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/1487/snow_patrol_to_release_greatest_hits|title=Snow Patrol to release 'GREATEST HITS'|date=12 March 2013|accessdate=15 March 2013|publisher=SnowPatrol.com}}</ref>\n\nSnow Patrol headlined the Tennent's Vital festival in August 2013 and performed a special warm-up show in London before the festival. After the show, the band announced that Simpson would leave the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thethirdbarcom.wordpress.com/2013/08/15/tom-simpson-leaving-the-band/|title=Tom Simpson Leaving The Band|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=15 August 2013|publisher=thethirdbar.com}}</ref> At their Tennent's Vital concert, Lightbody announced that it would be Simpson's last night with the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowpatrol.com/news/1661/toms_last_show_wth_sp |title=Snow Patrol Official Website :: News :: Tom's Last Show Wth Sp |publisher=Snowpatrol.com |date=16 August 2013 |accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Wildness'' (2018\u2013present)===\n[[File:20180603 N\u00fcrnberg Rock im Park Snow Patrol 0139.jpg|thumb|Lightbody performing with Snow Patrol at Rock im Park 2018]]\nThe follow-up to ''Fallen Empires'' was initially due for release in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://twitter.com/garysnowpatrol/status/618270067785007104 |title=Twitter Q&A \u2013 new Snow Patrol Music next year ...' |publisher=Twitter.com |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref> Previous reports suggested new material would be released in 2015. Lightbody told ''[[NME]]'' that he had to overcome a bout of [[writer's block]] and that the songs written for the new album were scrapped before being replaced by new \"mind-boggling\" material.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/snow-patrol/64572 |title=Snow Patrol scrap new album sessions &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2018, the band's social media announced the upcoming release of their seventh studio album, entitled ''[[Wildness (album)|Wildness]]'', which was released on 25 May 2018. The promotional video<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yow-gVc60cc |title=Youtube - Snow Patrol - Wildness' |publisher=Youtube.com |date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> simply showed lead singer Gary Lightbody floating on a raft with a piano and seemingly trying to phone someone who is engaged.\n\nThey embarked on their ''Wildness Tour'' to promote the album, and opened for [[Ed Sheeran]] during the autumn 2018 leg of his ''\u00f7 Tour'' in North America, in addition to their own headlining shows.\n\nIn November 2018, they released ''What If This All The Love You Ever Get?-EP'', featuring remixes of the track of the same name from ''Wildness''. The band released their third compilation album \"Reworked\" on 8 November 2019, to be followed by a tour.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/snow-patrol-reworked-uk-dates/ | title=Snow Patrol Announce Reworked UK, Irish Tour Dates| date=30 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/6431461/snow-patrol-chasing-second-shot-at-magic-on-reworked/|title=Snow Patrol chasing second shot at magic on Reworked|first=Josh|last=Leeson|date=11 October 2019|website=Newcastle Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nThe success of Snow Patrol has influenced the thriving Belfast music scene positively. This includes Lightbody, who returned to the city and now lives there. The band's kindness towards local bands, partly by founding Polar Music, and Lightbody being an active part of the [[Oh Yeah (music centre)|Oh Yeah Music Centre]] has resulted in high optimism in the scene.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/travel/2009/0919/1224254836875.html |title=Magical musical tour |last=Clayton-Lea |first=Tony |date=19 September 2009 |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kD1Q7sVJ |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nMusicians, such as [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Bono]] (of U2), [[Michael Stipe]] (of [[R.E.M.]]), and [[Nikki Sixx]] (of [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] and [[Sixx AM]]), have also expressed their admiration for Snow Patrol.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/bono-wants-snow-patrol-for-tour |title=U2 \u2013 Bono Wants Snow Patrol For Tour |date=31 January 2005|magazine=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=28 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.musicomh.com/music/features/rem-2_0408.htm |title=Interview: R.E.M. (2008) |last=Soghomonian |first=Talia |date=April 2008 |magazine=musicOMH |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ks9U3Dfk |archivedate=28 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/news/2009/nikki-sixx-im-an-artist-and-i-love-snow-patrol |title=Nikki Sixx: 'I'm an artist and I love Snow Patrol' |date=6 February 2009 |publisher=Xfm |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ks9ehQgw |archivedate=28 October 2009 }}</ref> [[Terri Hooley]], founder of the [[Good Vibrations (record label)|Good Vibrations]] label and a lifelong supporter of local Northern Irish music, has expressed pride in bands like Snow Patrol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/7298275.stm |title=Summer of teenage dreams remembered |last=Mitchell |first=Cameron |date=15 March 2008 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=4 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5llM7OcGw |archivedate=4 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nSnow Patrol have founded Polar Music, a publishing company run through Kobalt Music. The venture is independent from the band's publishing deal with [[Universal Music Group|Universal Music]]. Polar Music will sign artists regardless of their genre, as drummer Jonny Quinn explained: \"there is no agenda\u2014if it's good enough and we believe in it 110%, we will sign it.\" Quinn, and his fellow band members Connolly and Lightbody are acting as [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiachronicle.com/articles/yb/134919583 |title=New publishers on patrol |publisher=California Chronicle |accessdate=5 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5llNT0bc9 |archivedate=4 December 2009 }}</ref> The company's first signing was Johnny McDaid, previously of the Northern Irish band [[Vega4]].<ref name=\"PMUZAK\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3ifc174d5b0674b9dc13b5d62d9a88e91e |title=Snow Patrol Launches Publishing Venture |last=Wilson |first=Jen |date=3 September 2009 |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=5 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5llNV4Pme |archivedate=4 December 2009 }}</ref> Quinn has said that they wish to sign artists to a one-album deal, and do not want to put undue pressure on the artists with a bigger, multi-year deal.<ref name=\"PMUZAK\"/> Polar Music had its first chart hit in the first week of October 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/Gary-Lightbody-quite-busy-on-patrol-63717812.html |title=Gary Lightbody quite busy on patrol |last=Lanham |first=Tom |date=8 October 2009 |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Examiner]]|accessdate=8 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kNRIEmac |archivedate=8 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nGary Lightbody and Tom Simpson are both fans of the football club [[Dundee F.C.]] In 2008, they met the club's board of directors to find ways to financially help the short-of-cash club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2008/11/07/songwriting-has-made-me-a-better-person-says-snow-patrol-front-man-gary-lightbody-86908-20875466/ |title=Songwriting has made me a better person, says Snow Patrol front man Gary Lightbody |last=Dingwall |first=John |date=7 November 2008 |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |accessdate=10 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5llNQPtJx |archivedate=4 December 2009 }}</ref> The band also owns a stake in the Houndstooth Pub in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/22/AR2009052201105.html |title=In N.Y., an appetite for Gastropubs |last=Farley |first=David |date=24 May 2009 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=1 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kD8Ku2Sm |archivedate=1 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nOn 25 November 2007, Snow Patrol performed an acoustic session for the charity [[Mencap]], at [[Union Chapel, Islington]]. They were one of the main bands to take part in the project, called \"Little Noise Sessions\" which was curated by [[Jo Whiley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/mencap-little-noise-sessions-snow-patron-union-chapel-london-5337364.html|title=Mencap Little Noise Sessions: Snow Patron, Union Chapel, London|last=Hasted|first=Nick|date=2007-11-27|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=2019-05-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505154541/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/mencap-little-noise-sessions-snow-patron-union-chapel-london-5337364.html|archive-date=2019-05-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Magee|first=Kate|date=2007-11-02|title=Mencap strikes chord with Amazing Media|url=https://www.prweek.com/article/764482/mencap-strikes-chord-amazing-media|magazine=[[PRWeek]]|page=|pages=|doi=|pmid=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505154908/https://www.prweek.com/article/764482/mencap-strikes-chord-amazing-media|archive-date=2019-05-05|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Gary Lightbody and Nathan Connolly donated [[plectrum]]s and [[certificate of authenticity|certificate]]s to the Music Beats Mines project that aims to clear unexploded mines/landmines from conflict zones. The items were auctioned on eBay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/2009/11/27/radiohead-paul-mccartney-donate-items-to-online-charity-auction/|title=Radiohead, Paul McCartney donate items to online charity auction|last=Teo|first=Mark|date=27 November 2009|publisher=CHARTattack|accessdate=6 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728143932/http://www.chartattack.com/news/2009/11/27/radiohead-paul-mccartney-donate-items-to-online-charity-auction/|archive-date=28 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maginternational.org/musicbeatsmines/en/events/events/mbm-auction-items |title=MBM Auction items... |publisher=Mag International |accessdate=6 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5loMHhQWM |archivedate=6 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Gary Lightbody]] \u2013 lead vocals, rhythm guitar, piano, keyboards <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Jonny Quinn]] \u2013 drums, percussion <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Nathan Connolly]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2002\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Paul Wilson (musician)|Paul Wilson]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2005\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Johnny McDaid]] \u2013 keyboards, rhythm guitar, backing vocals <small>(2011\u2013present)</small>, <small>(Touring: 2007\u20132011)</small>\n\n'''Touring musicians'''\n* [[Richard Colburn]] \u2013 keyboards, drums, guitars, percussion <small>(1996\u20131997, 2008\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Iain Archer]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n* Colm MacAthlaoich \u2013 trumpet <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n* Miriam Kaufmann \u2013 backing vocals <small>(2006\u20132007, 2008\u2013present)</small>\n* Troy Stewart \u2013 guitar <small>(2008\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-2}}\n'''Former members'''\n* [[Mark McClelland]] \u2013 bass, keyboards, piano <small>(1994\u20132005)</small>\n* Michael Morrison \u2013 drums <small>(1994\u20131996)</small>\n* [[Tom Simpson (musician)|Tom Simpson]] \u2013 keyboards, piano, samples <small>(2005\u20132013)</small>, <small>(Touring: 1997\u20132005)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n'''Timeline'''\n<timeline>\nImageSize  = width:800 height:auto barincrement:30\nPlotArea   = left:120 bottom:115 top:05 right:10\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1994 till:01/01/2019\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend     = orientation:vert